WEBVTT

00:03.138 --> 00:05.000
Welcome to the Life Church Podcast.

00:06.442 --> 00:11.569
We are an Acts 2 42 community, a family on a mission to bring a life of Jesus to warranty.

00:13.131 --> 00:21.761
We hope you're ready to hear what God has to say to you today through His Word and by His Spirit.

00:21.782 --> 00:28.530
This morning we're going to think about, talk about, reflect upon

00:29.378 --> 00:36.168
And I trust activate the truth of what is perhaps arguably the central point of the gospel message of the Christian.

00:37.590 --> 00:42.717
And that is that Jesus Christ died for our sins.

00:43.779 --> 00:45.281
There was a price to be paid.

00:45.321 --> 00:47.484
There was a cost to bear.

00:47.524 --> 00:57.458
And Jesus in his own body on the cross paid a debt that we could not pay to live a life that we don't.

00:57.730 --> 00:58.251
deserve.

00:58.851 --> 01:06.700
Now many of you know that we being myself, my wife and at least two of our children, the third one, missed out on this season in life.

01:06.940 --> 01:14.088
We lived in Monaco for a while and as much as that was lovely to live by the ocean, one of the challenges of living in Monaco is the price.

01:15.310 --> 01:22.898
It's expensive and if it was down to us and our means we would probably just be living off bread and water

01:23.138 --> 01:24.159
while we were there.

01:24.580 --> 01:29.146
But what we did have to do was to trust in the means of other people.

01:29.787 --> 01:46.149
And so there would be times when we would be invited to a restaurant and you would sit down and the waiter would come over and they would pass you the menu and you would look at the menu and you would see all of these wonderful dishes all in a language that I didn't understand.

01:46.689 --> 01:50.194
But I knew enough to know there was some good stuff on the menu.

01:50.978 --> 01:55.142
but then just to the right hand side of the menu was the price.

01:57.824 --> 02:11.457
And so the menu told you all these amazing things that you could have on one condition, that there was somebody sat at the table who had the means to pay the price.

02:12.398 --> 02:16.662
Because without the payment, there was no substance.

02:17.103 --> 02:20.626
You wanted the substance somebody needed to meet.

02:20.706 --> 02:21.427
the payment.

02:21.868 --> 02:45.300
And fortunately, while the church wasn't replete with people of, it wasn't replete with millionaires and billionaires, so to speak, there were at times enough people that if we were invited out to dinner, we could look across them sheepishly and we could indicate to them through our body language and a kind of a shy smile, is it okay to trust you with the bill on this one?

02:45.340 --> 02:49.906
Otherwise, as I said, our diet would have been very, very different.

02:52.098 --> 03:09.607
And if we as Christians, and of course, if you are not a Christian, you want to enjoy the blessing of God, the favor of God, the goodness of God and the forgiveness of God, God the Father says there is a price to pay.

03:10.889 --> 03:19.122
Now, the problem for us is that none of us have the means to pay the price of that forgiveness, that goodness.

03:19.234 --> 03:20.095
and that favor.

03:20.596 --> 03:35.477
But Jesus himself stepped in our place, laid down his life, and with his own blood, he purchased the salvation of all who would look to him in faith.

03:36.098 --> 03:41.406
Just a couple of verses from Romans the book that we're studying this morning that describes some of the essence of this.

03:41.726 --> 03:47.154
Romans 6, 23 says, for the wages of sin is death.

03:47.714 --> 03:52.038
Not one of the wages, not one of the ways of paying sin is death.

03:52.279 --> 04:00.067
The only wage is death, unless somebody is there to pay the wages.

04:00.147 --> 04:10.938
Romans 5, 8, but God demonstrates his own love for us in this, that while we were still sinners, Christ died for us, paraphrase in our place.

04:12.560 --> 04:14.802
An Old Testament passage that we know and love

04:15.106 --> 04:41.010
Certainly we read it a lot here in this congregation, his Isaiah 53 and verse 5 says this, Our sin was upon him and by his wounds we are healed.

04:42.114 --> 04:53.512
It's the blood of Jesus, the sacrifice of Jesus, the death of Jesus that pays the sin price that we could not pay.

04:54.092 --> 05:02.866
There is power, there is power, wonder-working power in the blood of the Lamb.

05:04.098 --> 05:08.305
The evangelist Billy Graham, most of you I assume know who Billy Graham is.

05:08.345 --> 05:10.169
He's gone to be with the Lord some years ago.

05:10.189 --> 05:17.481
In 1955, he was given the opportunity to go and preach at Cambridge University.

05:18.122 --> 05:24.754
And because, as he believed, there were lots of people there who were going to be more scholarly than him,

05:24.994 --> 05:26.756
He had four nights to preach.

05:26.816 --> 05:33.443
And so he had prepared what he felt was a kind of a high-faluting message about Jesus.

05:33.463 --> 05:34.964
He'd done his research.

05:34.984 --> 05:51.762
He'd bought in, you know, some thoughts maybe from Sartre and some of the ancient philosophers and Plato and others that he felt that he could just build into the sermons that he was going to share so that people didn't think he was a dummy.

05:52.322 --> 06:05.958
And so for three nights out of four, he was preaching his message, drawing on the thoughts and the ideas of the people he felt would be passing as clever enough for the people to pay attention in the congregation.

06:05.979 --> 06:12.827
He had people like John Stott who was there helping him at his aid and some other people you might recognize that were in the audience.

06:12.907 --> 06:22.098
But he knew there were going to be plenty of people there in the congregation who felt that Cambridge University deserved a very sophisticated message.

06:23.650 --> 06:28.035
But at the end of the third night, Billy reflecting on what was happening, and that wasn't very much.

06:28.776 --> 06:30.458
There wasn't a great deal going on.

06:30.498 --> 06:43.555
So he made a decision that on the fourth night at the St Mary's Church, which was the main church that was used by Cambridge University, he was going to only preach about the blood of Jesus.

06:44.756 --> 06:46.258
Nothing else.

06:46.690 --> 06:59.581
And so he went on and talked about how from Genesis through to Revelation there was a theme about the sacrifice of blood being the thing that unlocked the power of God.

07:00.002 --> 07:03.250
He talked about that when Adam and Eve sinned

07:03.554 --> 07:12.186
Their fig leaf covering of their sin was insufficient, and God clothed them with animal skin, which by implication required the death of an animal.

07:12.566 --> 07:22.039
He talked about how Abel presented a sacrifice of the first fruits of his livestock, which was considered an acceptable offering to God.

07:22.379 --> 07:33.554
He talked about how Noah, after he came through the flood and then began to re-establish humanity after the flood, it says that he sacrificed animals as a thank offering to God

07:33.538 --> 07:34.339
after the flood.

07:34.599 --> 07:36.422
Now, let me just pause on that for a little moment.

07:36.742 --> 07:38.404
I felt that was quite funny this week.

07:38.464 --> 07:40.487
Imagine if you were one of the animals on the ark.

07:41.588 --> 07:45.093
And you thought, we just got away with one here.

07:45.133 --> 07:48.097
We made it through the flood.

07:48.717 --> 07:55.927
We heard all the wind blowing and howling and the rain and the storms and everything else, but we were one of the elect that got through.

07:55.987 --> 08:01.714
Only to find out when the doors opened on the ark, the first thing no one wanted to do was sacrifice some animals.

08:01.986 --> 08:07.771
Those poor animals that were part of that have had this false hope that they'd made it past the worst bit of it.

08:08.052 --> 08:09.433
Anyway, I move on, I digress.

08:10.334 --> 08:14.298
Abraham went to present Isaac his son upon a mountain.

08:14.878 --> 08:16.239
He didn't go through with that.

08:16.279 --> 08:17.541
God supplied a ram.

08:17.561 --> 08:22.825
It was caught in the bushes and God provide a substitute sacrifice.

08:23.626 --> 08:31.954
Israel, when it was going to be brought out of Egypt, God moved over the land of Egypt through bringing death

08:32.066 --> 08:41.946
on the firstborns in house, but God through the blood of a lamb applied to the doorposts would pass over all houses that applied the blood.

08:42.667 --> 08:52.427
And both Moses and Solomon in the tabernacle and the temple respectively understood the power of blood sacrifice on the altars.

08:53.609 --> 08:54.130
God

08:54.210 --> 09:01.357
throughout the whole of the Bible, he gives us a clear message that is repeated again and again and again and again.

09:01.397 --> 09:09.946
If you want me to pass over your sin, if you want me to move on from your punishment, then there has to be a sacrifice.

09:11.087 --> 09:14.050
Justice has to be served in some way.

09:15.151 --> 09:22.258
And the justice of God is satisfied in the substitute death of Jesus.

09:22.466 --> 09:37.407
The whole blessing of God, the whole of the package of the goodness of God is made available not on your merit, not on my merit, not on your goodness, but on the goodness, the faithfulness and the death of Jesus.

09:38.428 --> 09:39.490
And that's amazing news.

09:39.530 --> 09:51.346
That means that whether you have a good day or a bad day, whether you're on an up or a down, you're in a mountaintop experience or you're in the valley, the power of the cross is still available to you.

09:51.778 --> 09:54.142
Because it's not about you, it's about him.

09:54.162 --> 09:57.468
It's not about what you do, it's what Christ did.

09:57.828 --> 10:00.192
It's not what you can pay or you can afford.

10:00.453 --> 10:03.298
It's what the blood of Jesus has purchased for you.

10:03.338 --> 10:10.590
And so many times as Christians, we live as if our experience of God is dependent on our own merit.

10:11.171 --> 10:13.896
God, have I been good enough this week to deserve your goodness?

10:15.278 --> 10:17.682
God, have I been good enough to deserve your favor?

10:18.018 --> 10:21.887
God, have I been good enough for you to come through and answer my prayers?

10:23.010 --> 10:25.696
God is not looking to you for the payment.

10:26.778 --> 10:29.585
God has looked already to Jesus.

10:30.647 --> 10:32.873
It's for us to receive.

10:32.933 --> 10:35.198
It's Jesus who paid.

10:35.258 --> 10:36.882
It's like we're at

10:37.026 --> 10:45.020
that Monaco restaurant, and we're looking at all of the good things that God could supply us off the menu, but we're looking at each other.

10:45.320 --> 10:47.043
Who has got the means to pay?

10:47.344 --> 10:50.189
And Jesus says, it's all right, I've got my wallet.

10:51.511 --> 10:56.159
And the payment will be my life that I will lay down for you.

10:57.642 --> 10:59.986
So God has shown us in Scripture,

11:00.674 --> 11:11.729
The time and time again, the pattern is where there are problems, there are sin, there are issues with human failure, then the payment for those things is death.

11:12.271 --> 11:13.234
He initially

11:13.538 --> 11:19.505
allowed his relationship with his people to move forward based on the sacrifice of animals.

11:19.745 --> 11:21.066
But that was not enough.

11:21.347 --> 11:26.432
He knew that one day a true and perfect payment needed to be made.

11:26.632 --> 11:36.123
It was like those blood sacrifices of animals were kind of like building towards an like an IOU that eventually somebody had to pay the proper bill at the real price.

11:36.663 --> 11:37.644
And that was Jesus.

11:40.367 --> 11:42.770
And so Jesus dying for us.

11:43.042 --> 11:45.647
is the key that unlocks it all.

11:46.067 --> 11:54.081
And in the previous bits of Romans and they did a good job of sharing about this week, he made the case that all have sinned and all need this payment.

11:54.602 --> 12:03.858
There isn't anybody outside of Jesus himself who had the sufficient integrity and means and morality in order to pay the price that was owed.

12:04.578 --> 12:13.031
All of us have sinned and whether your mother to raise her or you were Adolf Hitler, everybody needed the blood of Jesus Christ to forgive them of their sins.

12:13.592 --> 12:16.997
There was not one righteous other than Jesus.

12:17.538 --> 12:20.583
There was not one good enough other than Jesus.

12:20.823 --> 12:23.768
There was not one worthy enough other than Jesus.

12:24.048 --> 12:33.202
There was no other who had the means but Jesus and no person will be ever able to stand before God and God look them in the eye and

12:33.314 --> 12:38.279
getting to heaven on the merit of all that they do, only on the work of Christ.

12:40.041 --> 12:42.263
But it's fair because it's open to all.

12:44.185 --> 12:50.391
God is willing that none should perish, but all should come to everlasting life.

12:52.313 --> 12:58.419
So what do we think about this more deeply in terms of justice?

12:58.479 --> 13:01.202
I reflect it as I prepared this message

13:03.682 --> 13:10.169
This presents some interesting challenges to our notion of justice.

13:10.189 --> 13:20.299
Now I have to this point kind of drawn an analogy between the payment of a bill and the release of the goodness of the menu to the work of Jesus.

13:21.701 --> 13:30.930
And I think sometimes when we reflect on the work of the cross and we think about the sacrifice of Jesus and the fact that God's justice is satisfied in his

13:31.266 --> 13:35.453
His, Jesus' sacrifice, the Father is satisfied in that.

13:36.915 --> 13:40.360
We think about this sense in which Jesus paid a price for us.

13:40.961 --> 13:44.967
Now, if we were to think about that in financial terms, that can make some sense.

13:45.028 --> 13:54.022
The idea that there is a bill to pay, we don't have the means for, and that substitute of Jesus' sacrifice or the Jesus' means to meet that payment is enough.

13:54.883 --> 13:56.786
But not all the sins

13:57.122 --> 14:04.573
A neat that the humans commit are neatly summed up in the idea of like the analogy of a financial payment.

14:08.118 --> 14:13.946
If the tragedy struck our house that one of my kids has lost his life and somebody else was responsible for that.

14:16.049 --> 14:22.098
And then my kids, sorry, my wife and my kids obviously left with the trauma of that, then there was a court appearance.

14:22.626 --> 14:28.074
And the person who was responsible for the death of one of my children was brought before the courts.

14:29.236 --> 14:37.369
And then somebody else offered to stand in their place for their crime, I wouldn't be happy.

14:38.310 --> 14:38.671
Would you?

14:38.711 --> 14:46.603
Would you be happy if the judge was to step down in place of the person who committed the crime?

14:47.445 --> 14:48.306
I don't think so.

14:49.506 --> 14:58.703
And so how do we, as Christians, reconcile some of the aspects of the justice of the cross?

14:59.264 --> 15:07.218
Now, there are numbers of different ways I could go into here of how theologians over the centuries have wrestled with this

15:07.746 --> 15:11.830
concept because in some ways we don't fully understand it.

15:11.910 --> 15:35.154
In other ways, we wrestle with it because we feel that there is something a little bit missing in our sense of how justice is satisfied in the substitution of Jesus because some of the things that Jesus has substituted himself for cannot be summed up adequately in the analogy of a paying of a bill, of a financial debt.

15:35.618 --> 15:38.120
there is something more significant going on.

15:38.461 --> 15:56.298
And it's interesting when you look back to King David's life, King David who ruled Israel, who was the kind of the beginner of the, what we would describe as the messianic line of Jesus' life, being King and Messiah from the line, the lineage, the genealogy of King David.

15:56.598 --> 16:04.626
There is this part in his life when he has seduced the wife of one of his

16:04.706 --> 16:08.832
most significant military commanders.

16:10.113 --> 16:13.177
A guy called Uriah, who was a Hittite.

16:14.880 --> 16:19.426
While the kings were supposed to be going to war, Uriah the Hittite was away.

16:19.847 --> 16:23.431
David spots this woman called Bathsheba, who he takes a fancy to.

16:25.174 --> 16:34.226
And he makes the situation work to his advantage that he ends up seducing this woman, and they have a union.

16:34.370 --> 16:40.718
That's, you know, Christians speak for coming together in a special way that adults come together.

16:44.023 --> 16:49.810
And then realizing that he was in a bit of a pickle with this, because this woman still had a husband, he tries to cover his tracks.

16:50.791 --> 16:58.962
And so what he does is he gets other people on his command to put Uriah at the front of the battle

16:59.778 --> 17:07.348
in order that the battle would kill Uriah and something of the kind of the process of war would do the dirty work for David.

17:07.729 --> 17:10.893
Now, initially this doesn't work, but eventually Uriah dies.

17:11.214 --> 17:15.340
And David feels like he's managed to get away with it.

17:17.102 --> 17:21.088
He thinks nobody has really found out, but God knew.

17:21.128 --> 17:28.658
And God sends his prophet Nathan to challenge David.

17:30.498 --> 17:38.371
And Nathan tells David this parable about this rich person taking this sheep from somebody else.

17:39.753 --> 17:42.117
And David is indignant because it's just like this.

17:42.217 --> 17:43.259
This is an injustice.

17:43.940 --> 17:44.681
This shouldn't have happened.

17:44.701 --> 17:45.202
That's not fair.

17:45.543 --> 17:47.345
And Nathan says, you're that man.

17:47.406 --> 17:48.888
That's you.

17:48.928 --> 17:49.809
That's what you've done.

17:49.850 --> 17:52.594
You have committed the injustice.

17:54.434 --> 18:03.929
And there was something evidently in David that I think is relevant to all human people to want to bury accountability for sin.

18:04.750 --> 18:08.055
That's the first thing, but God sees the second thing is this.

18:08.436 --> 18:22.898
And David says this interestingly in Psalm 51 verse four, when David then begins a process of repentance to God, he says against you,

18:23.234 --> 18:27.199
and you alone have I sinned."

18:28.501 --> 18:30.062
Now, I read that and I thought, hang on.

18:31.024 --> 18:33.947
No, no, no, no, not against God only of you sinned.

18:33.967 --> 18:39.314
If you were Uriah's parents, would you be happy that David said against you God only of us?

18:39.374 --> 18:45.461
And you'd be going, no, my family have also received the penalty of your sin.

18:46.062 --> 18:52.370
Don't just make this about you and God having a little bit of a quiet time and basically trying to kick it under the carpet.

18:53.346 --> 18:55.749
There are other people who face the consequences of this.

18:56.009 --> 18:58.872
The blood of the child cries out from the ground, justice.

19:01.015 --> 19:03.517
So how do we hold this together?

19:03.557 --> 19:07.081
Well, in the story of David, something interesting happens.

19:07.502 --> 19:14.950
God tells David that he shall not die, that his sins have been dealt with.

19:14.970 --> 19:21.938
But the consequences of his actions would not be stopped.

19:23.778 --> 19:32.950
there was a sense in which the sin has been dealt with by God, but the consequences of the sin still would rumble on.

19:34.812 --> 19:52.114
And I think what we get in the cross of Jesus is not God overlooking every aspect of justice, but satisfying the needs of justice to release the forgiveness of sins, but that doesn't mean that Christians can get away with murder.

19:54.690 --> 20:00.357
because God still believes in justice.

20:01.199 --> 20:04.203
The thief on the cross next to Jesus.

20:05.704 --> 20:11.412
There were two thieves on the cross, in fact, next to Jesus, one on his right and one on his left.

20:11.752 --> 20:15.598
And they get into a little bit of a debate about who this Jesus was.

20:15.918 --> 20:22.066
But one of them says, Lord, remember me when you come

20:22.242 --> 20:23.283
into your kingdom.

20:23.704 --> 20:29.410
And Jesus says to him, today you will be with me in paradise.

20:30.371 --> 20:33.595
How did that day end for the criminal?

20:33.635 --> 20:43.206
He still paid the price for his criminality, but the sin that would have kept him from the presence of God was dealt with in Jesus.

20:44.507 --> 20:50.354
He carried the penalty in his own back for the problems he had caused, but the sins

20:50.466 --> 20:52.750
penalty was paid for in Jesus.

20:53.832 --> 21:02.686
So I think we have to be careful as Christians when we proclaim the love and the forgiveness of God that we don't cheap and justice as we do so.

21:02.706 --> 21:14.866
Now I'm sure there will be some of you thinking okay okay well I get what you're saying but be careful Dave because sometimes God does allow humans to

21:15.170 --> 21:23.419
either receive a lighter sentence or to be allowed a pass on some consequences of their actions.

21:23.459 --> 21:40.357
There are stories that I've read, I believe, accredible, where people have maybe handed themselves into the police because of the conviction of sin of something that they did, and they were let off with some sort of pass, some sort of grace from the court system.

21:40.457 --> 21:44.882
And you would think that maybe if they hadn't have

21:45.506 --> 21:52.536
sought God's forgiveness, then maybe they might not have received such a kind of a commuted sentence.

21:54.099 --> 22:07.919
There are seemingly times in people's experiences when, because they followed Jesus and they sought him in repentance, he's allowed them to receive grace in the consequences of the things that they have done.

22:10.643 --> 22:12.946
That the punishment seems to be have

22:13.154 --> 22:14.996
have been more gentle in some way.

22:15.397 --> 22:21.844
But others, they have still paid the price to some degree for the consequences of their actions.

22:22.305 --> 22:33.879
King David was forgiven for his wrongdoing and stands today in the presence of Almighty God, but there were consequences to his actions.

22:36.322 --> 22:43.090
The injustice or the injustice of what he had done still required the fact that God couldn't just say, I can just

22:43.362 --> 22:44.885
shove all this under the carpet.

22:46.689 --> 22:56.571
I can't just pretend this didn't happen because there is love and mercy and grace but there is also justice as well in the cross of Jesus.

22:58.255 --> 23:01.522
And so when we preach the cross, when we preach the blood

23:02.338 --> 23:08.265
We are not saying you can do anything you want and get away with anything you want because Jesus paid for your sins.

23:08.926 --> 23:17.196
Jesus paid the full price for your sin, but that is not to say that justice isn't fair and right.

23:17.517 --> 23:31.794
And there are sometimes in the life, even of the believer, where we might like to get away with something, but God won't allow complete remission of consequence because he still upholds justice.

23:33.858 --> 23:37.683
And that's great when we're thinking God's are acting out and getting justice on our behalf.

23:38.003 --> 23:45.632
But what happens when we're the person who we want God to get justice, sorry, we're the person who somebody wants to get justice against, because something we have done.

23:45.672 --> 24:00.050
There are times when we have to accept the fact that in the discipline of the human life, God allows consequences of his way of disciplining us towards holiness.

24:00.546 --> 24:05.498
He allows consequences to happen to bring us towards repentance.

24:05.518 --> 24:11.794
He uses that stuff in grace to lead us to a closer relationship with him.

24:13.378 --> 24:21.570
And the final thing that we can do with all of this is that we then have to walk in a position of justice and grace in our own lives.

24:21.911 --> 24:24.775
We have to accept there are consequences to actions.

24:25.095 --> 24:28.921
There is sometimes justice that needs to take place in a human sense.

24:28.941 --> 24:30.784
There are things that will rumble on.

24:30.804 --> 24:33.888
There are consequences of actions that were done sometimes years ago.

24:34.189 --> 24:39.597
But in the midst of that, the grace and the goodness of God is that he is using that stuff.

24:39.637 --> 24:40.598
It's never wasted.

24:40.899 --> 24:43.122
It's not just punishment.

24:43.234 --> 24:44.075
discipline.

24:45.217 --> 24:52.889
He's not using it to whack you over the head and say, well, I've forgiven you, but I'm going to allow life to give you a real big kicking just because I think you deserve it.

24:54.711 --> 25:09.874
He will use all those things to lead us to greater and greater intimacy, to more and more holiness so that we can live lives that in terms of justice,

25:11.906 --> 25:17.895
would lead us away from the types of things that would cause negative consequences for our lives.

25:20.238 --> 25:25.145
We are people of truth and we are people of grace.

25:26.507 --> 25:28.330
And so your challenge this week is this.

25:30.032 --> 25:34.258
Your challenge is this week is think about those things

25:35.074 --> 25:42.301
where God is using hardship, maybe a consequence of a mistake or something to bring you and score you closer to Him.

25:43.523 --> 25:45.945
But also be prepared to walk in grace.

25:47.527 --> 26:02.642
I think one of the reasons why there is a bit of a mystery over the justice and the grace of the cross is because if all sin

26:02.914 --> 26:06.538
is owe to God, but there are consequences we often pay to one another.

26:06.578 --> 26:17.190
If God is the only one to whom we have sinned, he has the right and he has the right alone to choose the terms of how that is satisfied for him.

26:17.250 --> 26:23.617
And he is chosen to have his wrath and justice satisfied in the substitute death of Jesus.

26:25.339 --> 26:28.242
But he also requires us to choose

26:28.482 --> 26:36.810
to trust in the substitute death of Jesus as well, and to overlook at times the things in others where we would cry justice.

26:37.751 --> 26:51.765
So where God has said, I will allow myself to be satisfied in wrath and justice for sin in the substitute death of Jesus, to not go after the blood of others for what the blood of Jesus has paid.

26:52.105 --> 26:57.170
There are times when he then challenges us and saying, will you walk in that same grace?

26:58.530 --> 27:01.214
Were you walking that same mercy?

27:01.635 --> 27:08.184
Yes, there will be times when there are consequences that play out in our lives and consequences that will play out in the lives of others.

27:08.464 --> 27:14.573
There are still court appearances for wrongdoing, even for the believer at times.

27:14.794 --> 27:26.130
But there are moments when God puts in front of us an opportunity to walk in grace, to not ask for the justice we want from others because we are

27:26.722 --> 27:33.169
recipients of grace from Jesus and we too have to be prepared to offer grace to other people.

27:33.750 --> 27:48.126
We might feel at times, I deserve this from you but I am going to choose to trust that Jesus pays the price for sins and I got a gift that I don't deserve so I'm going to give you a gift that you don't deserve.

27:49.788 --> 27:51.730
I am going to allow you

27:52.098 --> 27:58.265
to be free from my anger and my bitterness and my frustration because that's what God has done for me.

27:58.305 --> 28:02.410
And that doesn't dilute justice.

28:03.071 --> 28:05.234
It just sets it in its proper place.

28:06.255 --> 28:16.087
It recognizes there are times when consequences come because of actions and God is not being ungracious to allow that to happen.

28:16.347 --> 28:18.610
He still upholds justice, but the

28:19.138 --> 28:23.182
penalty of sin, of consequences is satisfied in Jesus.

28:23.483 --> 28:28.408
And therefore he invites us to say, will you offer that grace to others?

28:28.909 --> 28:31.311
I have been satisfied in the death of my son for you.

28:31.351 --> 28:37.238
Will you be satisfied in the death of my son when you see and are confronted with the things that people have wronged against you?

28:37.278 --> 28:43.845
And so we are people of grace and we are people of truth.

28:44.846 --> 28:48.370
But ultimately it's the grace that shapes

28:48.930 --> 28:51.655
us ultimately.

28:54.640 --> 28:56.262
So this is the work of the cross.

28:56.282 --> 28:57.665
This is the work of Jesus.

28:57.725 --> 29:00.169
And this is the power of what we proclaim.

29:00.209 --> 29:06.941
I don't think I finished that story about Billy Graham.

29:06.981 --> 29:07.882
So I finished with this.

29:08.002 --> 29:12.530
He preached about the blood of Jesus, all those references that I gave you.

29:13.122 --> 29:23.862
And what happened at the end of that fourth night at Cambridge University that hadn't happened at any other night is 400 young men ran to the altar and gave their lives to the Lord.

29:25.866 --> 29:27.108
There is one report.

29:28.291 --> 29:34.322
I think it was from John Stott or another prominent Anken leader who's not with us anymore.

29:34.978 --> 29:45.154
that the Anglican movement inherited a great number of its leaders for the next generation from people who gave their lives to Christ on that evening under the Ministry of Billy Graham.

29:46.857 --> 29:48.820
He preached nothing but the blood of Jesus.

29:49.501 --> 29:57.414
He emptied himself of all clever sayings and the thoughts of every philosopher that he thought would satisfy the desires of those who were listening the previous nights.

29:57.835 --> 29:59.617
And he taught nothing else other than the blood.

30:00.920 --> 30:02.482
And four hundred

30:02.594 --> 30:05.780
documented salvation happen that night.

30:06.902 --> 30:08.786
There is power in the blood of Jesus.

30:09.567 --> 30:12.012
That does not overlook justice.

30:12.332 --> 30:21.930
It satisfies it and gives God the possibility to offer grace while not overlooking justice.

30:22.712 --> 30:25.938
And then the consequence of that is for us, there are times when we get

30:26.146 --> 30:27.607
Don't get what we deserve.

30:27.948 --> 30:35.855
And there are other times when God will allow us to get what we deserve in part to teach us a lesson, to bring us back to walking closer with him.

30:36.155 --> 30:38.237
Because he doesn't dismiss justice.

30:39.318 --> 30:43.142
He is just handled in a certain way in the blood and the sacrifice of Christ.

30:44.924 --> 30:48.447
And we are to now walking grace and truth.

30:50.409 --> 30:53.172
Grace and truth.

30:54.513 --> 30:55.794
Let's close our eyes.

30:56.674 --> 31:00.198
I'm going to read the verses of a song over you.

31:00.258 --> 31:15.097
We sung a modern rendition of this song earlier, but the lyrics I'm going to share with you are the original lyrics of this hymn.

31:17.019 --> 31:20.604
Just allow the Holy Spirit to minister these words to your spirit.

31:21.405 --> 31:24.268
If there are things you need to confess to God, confess them.

31:24.889 --> 31:25.810
I'm not going to come

31:26.434 --> 31:28.196
on behalf of justice and punish you.

31:29.357 --> 31:36.764
Bring all of those things to the feet of Jesus, and repentance will release you from the punishment of sin.

31:36.804 --> 31:42.649
But also think, who, because of what Jesus has done, do I need to show mercy to?

31:42.689 --> 31:45.312
The verse of this old hymn goes like this.

31:46.533 --> 31:48.995
Would you be free from the burden of sin?

31:49.055 --> 31:53.720
There is power, power in the blood.

31:54.560 --> 31:56.402
Would you, over evil,

31:56.642 --> 31:57.843
a victory win.

31:57.884 --> 32:00.587
There is wonderful power in the blood.

32:01.588 --> 32:07.816
There is power, power, wonder-working power in the blood of the Lamb.

32:07.856 --> 32:14.604
There is power, power, wonder-working power in the precious blood of the Lamb.

32:15.325 --> 32:17.908
Would you be free from your passion and pride?

32:18.188 --> 32:19.730
There is power in the blood

32:20.034 --> 32:21.436
There is power in the blood.

32:21.937 --> 32:24.801
Come for a cleansing to calvary's tide.

32:25.262 --> 32:27.265
There is wonderful power in the blood.

32:28.066 --> 32:33.695
There is power, power, wonder-working power in the blood of the Lamb.

32:33.715 --> 32:40.626
There is power, power, wonder-working power in the precious blood of the Lamb.

32:40.738 --> 32:45.584
The final verse says, would you be whiter, much whiter than snow?

32:45.985 --> 32:49.670
There is power in the blood, there is power in the blood.

32:50.291 --> 32:54.777
Sin stains are lost in its life giving flow.

32:55.438 --> 32:59.964
There is wonderful power in the blood.

33:01.125 --> 33:10.738
Father over your family, your sons and your daughters, this morning over myself, we declare where there is confession of sin, there is remission of sin.

33:11.106 --> 33:14.815
where there is confession of wrongdoing, there is forgiveness for wrongdoing.

33:15.257 --> 33:23.558
Not one jot of the power of sin can remain where the blood of Jesus has washed it away.

33:24.801 --> 33:28.370
But Lord God, we do also seek justice.

33:28.482 --> 33:46.519
as we walk in mercy, both for ourselves and for others, and we pray that we will be people of grace, shaped with thankfulness for what you have paid, the price that we could not pay to live a life that we don't deserve because of all the things that Jesus did.

33:46.960 --> 33:48.521
We just say thank you.

33:48.901 --> 33:55.107
We thank you, God, for the power of the blood of Jesus that makes us white as snow.

33:55.127 --> 33:57.970
In Jesus' name we pray,

33:58.210 --> 34:02.302
We've come to the end of this week's message.

34:02.903 --> 34:04.568
We hope you've been impacted and inspired.

34:05.391 --> 34:12.210
Please keep up-to-date with everything that's happening by visiting our websites at www.livechurchburrington.com.

